{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496899"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:59:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1433"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1433"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.1,0.74,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1433"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4734"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33974"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 6-hour history of pain which came on rapidly in her lower abdomen. She does not feel nauseated and has not vomited. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 114/80 mmHg, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. There is tenderness in her right iliac fossa and the rest of the abdomen is soft to palpation. Urine dipstick is normal and a pregnancy test is negative. Blood tests show leukocytosis with elevated neutrophils. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed and a representative slice is shown (Image).\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caecal carcinoma","Ascending colon foreign body","Appendicitis","Meckel\u0027s diverticulum","Superior mesenteric artery syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a large, swollen appendix seen in the typical position (Image). CT is becoming more common in the investigation of possible \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst this investigation has a high sensitivity, a negative finding does not necessarily exclude the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETypical CT findings of appendicitis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEnlarged appendiceal diameter \u0026gt;6 mm with an occluded lumen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppendiceal wall thickening (\u0026gt;2 mm)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeriappendiceal fat stranding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppendiceal wall enhancement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppendicolith (seen in approximately 25 percent of patients)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaecal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in the older population. Moreover, these patients usually present with occult bleeding or melaena or manifestations of iron deficiency anaemia (due to chronic bleeding. Caecal carcinoma may be noted as exophytic lesion and/or caecum narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeckel\u0027s diverticulum \u003C/strong\u003Eusually presents before the age of two and if symptomatic, it presents with symptoms of lower gastrointestinal bleeding. Anatomically, it is located two feet proximal to the ileocaecal valve. The imaging study would be 99mtc pertechnetate to look for ectopic gastric mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior mesenteric artery syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E presents with proximal small bowel obstruction following compression of the third portion of the duodenum in between the aorta and the superior mesenteric artery. It results from a narrowing of the aorto-mesenteric angle which may occur congenitally, or may be acquired following sudden, extreme weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFaecal material can be seen in the ascending colon and there is no evidence of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eforeign body\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A large, swollen appendix seen on CT is consistent with a diagnosis of appendicitis."],"references":["Bax T, Macha M, Mayberry J.  The utility of CT scan for the diagnostic evaluation of acute abdominal pain. American J Surg 2019; 217: 959-66 Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30824170/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1433"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15622"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20659"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15622"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a6af77c-54b4-46ba-8563-0f28c6a69803.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a6af77c-54b4-46ba-8563-0f28c6a69803.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":400,"height":573}},{"type":"media","id":"20659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici